
OBJECTIVE
•	To implement a digital object counting system using an LPC2148 microcontroller, an IR sensor, and an LCD display. The system increments a count every time an object obstructs the IR beam and displays the total 
  count in real-time on the LCD screen.

ALGORITHM

1.	System Initialization:
    o	Configure GPIO pins for the LCD (Control pins: P0.8, P0.11; Data port: P1.16–P1.23).
    o	Configure the IR sensor pin (P0.16) as an input.
    o	Initialize the LCD by sending specific command codes (0x38, 0x01, 0x06, 0x0C, 0x80).
2.	Display Initialization: Write the static string "Object Count:" to the first line of the LCD.
3.	Main Loop:
    o	Check Sensor: Read the logic level of the IR sensor (P0.16).
    o	Detection: If the sensor is low (object detected) AND the object_detected flag is 0:
        *	Increment the count variable.
        *	Update the object_detected flag to 1.
        *	Update the LCD display by printing the updated count on the second line (0xC0).
    o	Reset: If the sensor is high (no object), reset the object_detected flag to 0 to prepare for the next object.
    o	Stability: Execute a small delay to debounce the sensor signal.

CODE

#include <nxp\iolpc2148.h>
#define rs IO0PIN_bit.P0_8
#define en IO0PIN_bit.P0_11
#define IR_INPUT IO0PIN_bit.P0_16  // IR sensor connected to P0.16
unsigned char commandarray[5] = {0x38, 0x01, 0x06, 0x0C, 0x80};
void delay(unsigned int x)
{
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < x; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 500; j++);
}
void command()
{
    int i;
    for(i = 0; i < 5; i++)
    {
        IO1PIN = commandarray[i] << 16;
        rs = 0;
        en = 1;
        delay(5);
        en = 0;
        delay(5);
    }
}
void lcd_cmd(unsigned char cmd)
{
    IO1PIN = cmd << 16;
    rs = 0;
    en = 1;
    delay(5);
    en = 0;
}
void lcd_data(unsigned char data)
{
    IO1PIN = data << 16;
    rs = 1;
    en = 1;
    delay(5);
    en = 0;
}
void lcd_string(unsigned char *str)
{
    while(*str)
    {
        lcd_data(*str++);
    }
}

void lcd_display_number(unsigned int num)
{
    unsigned char str[5];
    int i = 0;

    if(num == 0)
    {
        lcd_data('0');
        return;
    }
    while(num > 0)
    {
        str[i++] = (num % 10) + '0';
        num = num / 10;
    }
    while(i > 0)
    {
        lcd_data(str[--i]);
    }
}
void main()
{
    unsigned int count = 0;
    unsigned char object_detected = 0;
    // LCD pin setup
    PINSEL0 = 0x00000000;
    PINSEL1 = 0x00000000;
    PINSEL2 = 0x00000000;

    IO0DIR_bit.P0_8 = 1;   // RS
    IO0DIR_bit.P0_11 = 1;  // EN
    IO1DIR = 0x00FF0000;   // P1.16 P1.23 as output for LCD data
    IO0DIR_bit.P0_16 = 0;   // IR sensor input (P0.16 as input)
    command();
    lcd_cmd(0x80);
    lcd_string("Object Count:");

    while(1)
    {
        if(IR_INPUT == 0 && object_detected == 0)
        {
            object_detected = 1;   // Object detected
            count++;

            lcd_cmd(0xC0);          // Move to 2nd line
            lcd_display_number(count);
        }
        if(IR_INPUT == 1)
        {
            object_detected = 0;   // Object moved away
        }

        delay(50);  // Debounce delay
    }
}

PROCEDURE

1.	Project Creation: Open IAR, create a new C project, and select NXP LPC2148 as the target device.
2.	Coding: Create a new main.c file, paste the code, and add it to the project workspace.
3.	Project Options: * Right-click the project → Options.
    o	General Options: Confirm Device is "NXP LPC2148".
    o	Output Converter: Select "Generate additional output" and choose Intel Extended HEX.
4.	Compilation: Go to Project > Make (F7). Ensure there are no errors in the build log.
5.	Hardware Interfacing:
    o	LCD: Connect the LCD data bus (D0-D7) to P1.16 through P1.23. Connect RS to P0.8 and Enable (EN) to P0.11.
    o	IR Sensor: Connect the output of the IR sensor module to P0.16.
    o	Power: Ensure the LCD and IR sensor are provided with appropriate +5V power and ground.
6.	Flashing: Upload the generated .hex file to the LPC2148 kit using Flash Magic.
7.	Testing: Power the circuit. The LCD will display "Object Count:". Interrupt the IR beam; the number on the LCD will increment for every object that passes.

